Three-reviewer consensus on R1. Two-reviewer consensus on the Layer null bug.

**Fixes shipped (v0.7.0, breaking ƒ?" closes the iter-1 regression):**

- **R1 (Critical, three-reviewer consensus, iter-1 regression of C1):** the C1 `ReadOnlyTransactionWorld` denylist was missing 9+ real mutating methods on `World` (`random`, `setResourceMax`, `setProduction`, `setConsumption`, `start`, `stop`, `pause`, `resume`, `setSpeed`, `onDestroy`, `offDestroy`, `onTickFailure`, `offTickFailure`, `onCommandResult`, `offCommandResult`, `onCommandExecution`, `offCommandExecution`) and contained 6 spurious entries (`registerComponentOptions`, `setTickFailureListener`, `setCommandResultListener`, `setCommandExecutionListener`, `setOnDestroy`, `rebuildSpatialIndex`). The most damaging gap: `random()` mutates `DeterministicRandom.state`, so a side-effecting predicate that called `w.random()` advanced the RNG even on `precondition_failed`, **breaking the engine's determinism contract and snapshot-replay correctness**. Fix: introduced `FORBIDDEN_PRECONDITION_METHODS` const array as a single source of truth. The type-level `Omit` derives from `(typeof FORBIDDEN_PRECONDITION_METHODS)[number]`; the runtime `Set` derives from the same array. Drift between the two lists is now impossible by construction. Added a property-based regression test that iterates the array and asserts every method throws when called from a precondition; explicit tests pin the headline cases (`random()`, `setProduction`, lifecycle methods).

  **Note on the casted-internal escape Codex raised:** TypeScript `private` is type-only, so a determined caller can still cast to `any` and reach `gameLoop`/`rng` directly. The proxy doesn't block that escape. Closing it would require a switch to an allowlist proxy that only forwards known read methods ƒ?" purer but adds maintenance burden as new read methods are added to `World`. The current denylist is exhaustive against the public surface, which is what the contract promises. The doc explicitly notes this caveat.

- **H_NEW1 (Gemini + Opus High, two-reviewer consensus):** `Layer.forEachReadOnly` used `cb(stored ?? this._defaultValue, ...)`. The `??` operator treats `null` as nullish, so a cell explicitly set to `null` (with a non-null `defaultValue`) read back as `defaultValue`. Repro: `new Layer<number | null>({ ..., defaultValue: 0 }).setCell(0, 0, null)` then `forEachReadOnly` yielded `0` instead of `null`. Sibling `forEach` correctly uses `=== undefined`. Fix: replaced `??` with `=== undefined` to match. New regression test on `Layer<number | null>` with explicit-null cell.

- **H_NEW2 (Codex High):** the H4 primitive fast-path was computed once from `defaultValue` and reused for every value. For `Layer<unknown>` or `Layer<number | { n: number }>` with a primitive default + later object writes, the object would be stored without cloning, returned without cloning, and copied into `clone()` by reference ƒ?" breaking the defensive-copy contract for mixed-type layers. Fix: introduced a `cloneIfNeeded(value)` helper that decides per-value via `isImmutablePrimitive(value)` rather than the cached `_defaultIsPrimitive`. The cached default-primitivity flag is now `_defaultIsPrimitive` and is used only by `matchesDefault` (which compares the value against the fixed default). New regression test for `Layer<unknown>` with primitive default + object write.

- **M_NEW1 + M_NEW2 (Opus + Gemini Medium):** `Layer.setCell`/`setAt`/`fill` and `Layer.fromState` were paying double JSON-compat validation per write/load ƒ?" `assertJsonCompatible(value)` explicit + `jsonFingerprint(value)` (which calls `assertJsonCompatible` internally per `json.ts:60`). Fix: branch on `_defaultIsPrimitive`. For primitive-default layers, skip `jsonFingerprint` (use direct `===` for default-equality) and validate explicitly via `assertJsonCompatible`. For object-default layers, use `jsonFingerprint` and rely on its internal validation. Each value pays exactly one validation walk per boundary.

- **L_NEW1 (Gemini Low):** `CommandTransaction.commit()` early-throw at the top of the method hardcoded `'CommandTransaction already committed'`. After `tx.abort()` + `tx.commit()` (which sets `status='committed'` while keeping `terminalReason='aborted'`) + `tx.commit()`, the second commit threw "already committed" instead of "already aborted". Fix: read `terminalReason` instead of hardcoding the string.

- **L_NEW2 (Gemini Low):** `Layer.clone()` passed `structuredClone(this._defaultValue)` to the constructor, which itself defensive-clones ƒ?" double clone per `clone()` call for object T. Fix: pass `this._defaultValue` by reference.

- **L_NEW3 (Opus Low):** `Layer.getState()` had a defensive `if (jsonFingerprint(value) === this._defaultFingerprint) continue;` filter. Post-H2 strip-at-write, every public path that inserts strips defaults ƒ?" and `cells` is `private`, so no public bypass exists. Dead code. Removed.

- **L_NEW4 (Codex Low):** `World.warnIfPoisoned(api)` was made public in v0.6.0 but absent from `docs/api-reference.md`. Added a section between `recover()` and `start()`.

- **L_NEW5 (Opus Low):** stale test name `setCell with default value still stores the marker (round-trips)` referenced pre-H2 behavior. Renamed to `setCell back to default value reads back as default (post-H2 strip-at-write)`.

- **L_NEW7 (Codex Low):** added explicit `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER + 1` regression test for M2's deserialize tick validation. Behavior was covered transitively (same throw path); the new test pins it.

**Acknowledged residual (deliberately not fixed):**

- **L_NEW6 (Opus Low):** one `eslint-disable @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` survives in `CommandTransaction.commit()`'s `world.emit` dispatch line. Buffered events store as the loose `BufferedEvent = { type: string; data: unknown }` shape, and tightening this requires either a more invasive typed-event-buffer redesign or accepting the dispatch cast as the residual cost of buffering. The runtime is correct (`EventBus.emit` re-validates payloads). The L6 fix in v0.6.0 eliminated the `as unknown as World<..., any, any, any>` cast at `world.transaction()`, which was the headline; this lone `any` at the dispatch site is the residual cost of preserving event buffering.

- **N1 (circular import smell):** `src/world-internal.ts` imports `SYSTEM_PHASES` from `world.js` while `world.ts` imports value functions from `world-internal.js`. Works today via ES module live bindings + use-inside-function-bodies. Cleanup queued for the deeper world.ts split (which has its own dedicated branch in the M3 deferral note).

**Reasoning:** Bundled iter-2 fixes into one commit because the C1 re-fix, Layer correctness fixes, and Layer perf fixes all touch overlapping surfaces ƒ?" splitting them would have meant two transitions of `command-transaction.ts` (FORBIDDEN list + commit terminal-reason fix) and three transitions of `layer.ts` (forEachReadOnly + primitive fast-path + double-validate + clone + getState dead). One coherent commit per the "one version bump per coherent shipped change" rule.

Per AGENTS.md tests-first: 8 new tests added (5 in command-transaction: property-based FORBIDDEN, random, setProduction, lifecycle methods, double-commit-aborted; 2 in layer: forEachReadOnly null, Layer<unknown> object write; 1 in serializer: MAX_SAFE_INTEGER + 1) before any source change.

**Result:** 600 tests pass (up from 592). Typecheck, lint, build all clean.

